Loan Default Prediction Model¶

February 5, 2020

This notebook contains the solution to the BFS Capital interview assignment. It represents a baseline model for predicting which loan issued in 2016 are charge offs. For answers to Q1 and Q2 of the assignment, please scroll to the bottom of the notebook

Note that the model developed in this notebook is for demonstration purposes. When I write code for production, they are typically in version controlled Python scripts organized according to the various steps required for model development.

Assumptions¶

  • Restrict loans to just "completed" loans: Fully Paid and Charged Off.
    • These two categories marks the end of a loan. Loans that are current, in default, or in grace period may become fully paid or a charge off in the future.
  • Model will be used in 2016, thus training will use loans issued from years before 2016
    • Training data years: 2013, 2014, 2015
    • Out-of-sample year: 2016
  • Model will be used only on most recent data. As such, features containing data that will not be available at the time when the model will be used is excluded
  • Columns that have more than 40% of their observation missing are not useful

References¶

  • Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/wordsforthewise/lending-club
  • Kernel source:
    • https://www.kaggle.com/pileatedperch/predicting-charge-off-from-initial-listing-data
    • https://www.kaggle.com/sishihara/simple-lightgbm-kfold

Data preprocessing and filtering¶

Restrict to "completed" loans¶

From https://www.kaggle.com/pavlofesenko/minimizing-risks-for-loan-investments

Loan status description from the Lending Club:

  • Current: Loan is up to date on all outstanding payments.
  • In Grace Period: Loan is past due but within the 15-day grace period.
  • Late (16-30): Loan has not been current for 16 to 30 days.
  • Late (31-120): Loan has not been current for 31 to 120 days.
  • Fully paid: Loan has been fully repaid, either at the expiration of the 3- or 5-year year term or as a result of a prepayment.
  • Default: Loan has not been current for an extended period of time.
  • Charged Off: Loan for which there is no longer a reasonable expectation of further payments.

Define target variable¶

The target feature for this dataset is an indicator if the loan is Charged Off (1) or Fully Paid (0). As expected, the target is imbalanced (with a ratio of 4 paid loans to 1 charge off). This will inform the objective function we will use in training (i.e. ROC-AUC vs Precision-Recall AUC)

In [5]:

df['target'] = 1
df['target'] = (df['target'].
                where(df['loan_status'] == 'Charged Off', 0))
df = df.drop('loan_status', axis=1)

Drop columns with >40% missing¶

In [7]:
def get_high_missing_cols(df, thresh=40):
    count = 0
    missing_cols = []
    num_records = len(df)
    for c in df.columns:
        perc_missing = (df[c].isna().sum() / num_records)*100
        if perc_missing > thresh:
            print(f"{c} has {perc_missing:.3f}% missing")
            count += 1
            missing_cols.append(c)
    print(f"Num cols with more than {thresh}% missing: {count}")
    return missing_cols

Variables at loan application time¶

Because the dataset is a historical snapshot, not all variables in the data are available to LC at the time a loan application is being evaluated. For example, the variable total_pymnt measures the payments received to date for the total amount funded for a given loan. The value for this comes long after the lifecycle of a loan is completed (where it ends at either being 'Fully Paid' or 'Charged Off'). As such, at the time a loan application is being evaluated, information from this feature is unavailable.

To get the list of variables available at loan application time, I borrow the list of variables to keep from work undertaken in this Kaggle notebook

https://www.kaggle.com/pileatedperch/predicting-charge-off-from-initial-listing-data

We exclude emp_title because of the inconsistent classification used across loan applications. For example, nurses could be classified as a 'Nurse', 'Registered Nurse', 'RN', etc. This is an important category, but I suspect that it will likely be highly correlated with income.

The variables 'title' and 'purpose' captures similar information. 'purpose' however has lower cardinality and the classes appears to be standardized. As such, we exclude 'title' from our list of categorical variables.

From the summary above, we classify each categorical as follows.

Modelling¶

I use LightGBM for the baseline model. The model is widely used in Kaggle competitions and is suitable for this problem given the amount of data available. I train and validate in 2013-2015 (inclusive) and evaluate the model in 2016. I do very little feature engineering besides identifying categorical features and passing in the variable names of these features into LightGBM (an approach that is know to improve model performance). I also allow LightGBM to make the decision on how to treat null values.

My modelling approach follows the technique on this page. I fit K models across the K folds using cross validation. For each fold, I set LightGBM to stop training if the validation error fails to improve within 200 iterations. I use the average prediction made by each K models as the final prediction for the evaluation set (2016 loan application data). Because the classes are imbalanced, I use the average precision score as the objective function to maximize.

Other approaches I could have taken to preprocess the categorical features include

  • Encoding ordinal categorical features by assigning them a numeric ranking
  • Applying either one-hot or target encoding (for high cardinality categorical features) on the nominal categorical features

def avg_precision_score(y_true, y_pred):
    '''average precision score for the LightGBM Sklearn API
    Source: https://github.com/microsoft/LightGBM/issues/2182
    '''
    is_higher_better = True
    return 'avg_precision_score', metrics.average_precision_score(y_true, y_pred), is_higher_better
In [25]:
def train_lgbm(df_train, n_splits):
    lgb_params = {
        'objective': "binary",
        'boosting': "gbdt",
        'n_estimators': 2000,
        'learning_rate': 0.01,
        'num_leaves': 50,
        'min_data_in_leaf': 50,
        'colsample_bytree': .8,
        'subsample': .9,
        'max_depth': 8,
        'reg_alpha': .1,
        'reg_lambda': .1,
        'min_split_gain': .01,
        'min_child_weight': 2,
        'bagging_fraction': .5,
        'bagging_freq':100,
        'scale_pos_weight':2
    }

    eval_metric = avg_precision_score
#     eval_metric = 'auc'

    val_preds = np.zeros(X_train.shape[0])
    models = []

    folds = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    for n_fold, (trn_idx, val_idx) in enumerate(folds.split(df_train)):

        trn_x, trn_y = X_train[all_cols].iloc[trn_idx], y_train.iloc[trn_idx]
        val_x, val_y = X_train[all_cols].iloc[val_idx], y_train.iloc[val_idx]

        lgb_model = LGBMClassifier(**lgb_params)
        lgb_model.fit(trn_x, trn_y,
                eval_set=[(trn_x, trn_y), (val_x, val_y)], 
                eval_metric=eval_metric, 
                verbose=200, 
                early_stopping_rounds=200,
                categorical_feature=all_cats_cols)
        
        # Generate predictions based on best num. of iterations
        # and save to an array
        best_iter = lgb_model.best_iteration_
        val_preds[val_idx] = lgb_model.predict_proba(val_x, 
                                               num_iteration=best_iter)[:, 1]

        print(f"Best number of iteration for fold {n_fold}: {best_iter} \n")

        # Save models for oos prediction
        models.append(lgb_model)

    print('ROC AUC: %.6f' % roc_auc_score(y_train, val_preds))
    print('PR AUC: %.6f' % metrics.average_precision_score(y_train, val_preds))
    return models, val_preds

Q1: Visualizing predictions for each month of 2016¶

Here we compute the log loss for each record in the evaluation set and plot the average values and confidence interval for each month of 2016. From the lineplot, we observe a deterioration of the model performance with time. It is clear that there is a statistically significant difference between the average log loss in the first few months compared with subsequent months.

The second plot shows the deciles of the predictions (x-axis), plotted againts the number of charge offs in the decile (y-axis). More concretely, the height of the bar graph in each decile represents the number of charge offs in that decile. The 9th decile are the loan applications that are in the top 10 percent in probability of being a charge off. A deterioration occurs when the count of charge offs in the lower deciles increases relative to the count of charge offs in the top deciles. Looking at the counts of charge offs across the deciles over the year, this appears to be the case.

from math import log
def logloss1(y, p):
    return -(y*log(p) + (1 - y)*log(1 - p))

Q2: Revenue analysis¶

To explore why revenues might have increased from using the model, we can look at a summary of the features between loans that are most likely to be a charge off and loans that are more likely to be paid off based on the predictions of the model. Below is the decile plot for all loan applications in 2016.

I split the 2016 dataset between those in the top deciles (deciles 7, 8 and 9) and compare their features with those in the bottom deciles (deciles 0, 1, and 2). Deciles are based on the predicted probabilities (the 9th decile represent the top 10 percent in predicted probabilities---those most likely to be charge offs).

Comparing the distribution of the features, the FICO scores (both low and high) are higher for those in the lower deciles (good borrowers). Similarly, interest rates are lower for this group. For the group in the upper deciles (bad borrowers), their FICO scores are lower and they also have a higher average interest rate.

High interest rates may result in higher expected revenue, but only if loans are paid at the end of their term. If the borrower's loan results in a charge off, we not only lose interest revenue, but the loan principal itself. The revenue may have increased because the model helped guide us to select only "good" borrowers.
